    "You push the heavy door and it gives with a familiar creak, the sound of something that has been opened and closed a hundred quiet times. The pendant at your throat is cold; the shell presses into your sternum like an old question you have not yet answered."
    "The greenhouse air folds around you — humid, green, a close smell of wet soil and copper. Potted marsh grasses lean toward the glass. A teaching board is propped against a table; schematics, brittle at the"
    "edges, are tacked above it. Your notebooks are where you left them, pages dog-eared with half-drawn contour lines."

    scene bg ch2_c4ca42_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Cello drifts lower, a single sustained tone]
    "You stand at the table. The map of channels and hardened levees looks like a wound neatly stitched. Your name — a little note in the margin — sits underlined, unchanged by time. For a second"
    "you only look. The lab smells like damp cardboard and the sea; the world outside is a muted watercolor."
    "You touch the corner of a schematic. Your finger hesitates over a torn margin where salt once tracked. The memory of the work — the hours spent arguing models and budgets, the meeting that favored efficiency"
    "over marsh reeds — makes your chest tight. You can feel the smallness of that room and, behind it, the long list of what you couldn't protect."

