    menu:
        "Put the schematic back, steady yourself":
            "You smooth the paper down and step back. Your palms flatten against your thighs as if to hold yourself together. You breathe once, reminding yourself that you can listen first, speak later."
        "Trace the old annotation with your fingertip":
            "Your fingertip follows the faded ink; the route you recommended is there, a thin line that becomes a bridge and a bruise at once. The motion makes a small ache — responsibility turning tactile."

    menu:
        "Sketch a rough concept on the margin: 'living thresholds'":
            "Your pencil moves, tentative at first, and the page leans into a new language of layered lines and soft edges. The idea feels tender as a reed; an act of faith more than a blueprint."
        "Fold the paper away, keep the idea in your head for now":
            "You fold the schematic inward and tuck the idea behind your ribs. It stays warm there, private — safer from the politics for one breath."

